{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "While the PLD does not explicitly distinguish between different defect types, 47 it leaves room for differentiating liability by requiring courts to consider \"all circumstances\" when assessing legitimate safety expectations.",
    "This includes factors like product presentation, reasonable use, and the timing of the product's introduction.",
    "48 The presentation of the product consists of how the producer markets the product and what instructions the producer provides (Wuyts, 2014, 16).",
    "49 By considering these factors, courts can give more weight to either the producers' or consumers' responsibility, depending on the case's particular circumstances.",
    "50 Furthermore, laws transposed in various EU Member States include elements resembling the American distinction between manufacturing and design defects, 51 and national courts have referred to these distinctions."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "48 The presentation of the product consists of how the producer markets the product and what instructions the producer provides (Wuyts, 2014, 16).",
